{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a27d295a-a066-48b6-916e-358dd5b26b77","content":"The template.json is **not quite ready** for NuGet publishing. Here's what I found:\n\n**✅ Good — required fields present:**\n- `identity`, `name`, `shortName`, `author`, `sourceName`, `classifications`, `tags`\n\n**⚠️ Issues to fix:**\n\n1. **Missing `$schema`** — Add it for tooling/validation support.\n2. **Missing `groupIdentity`** — Critical for NuGet. Without it, package updates can install duplicate templates instead of replacing the old one.\n3. **`Framework` symbol has no `replaces`** — The parameter is defined but never wired to substitute anything (e.g., the TFM in a `.csproj`). It won't actually do anything as-is.\n4. **No template content** — The directory has no source files (`.csproj`, `Program.cs`, etc.) for the template to scaffold.\n5. **No `.nuspec` or packaging project** — You'll need a `.csproj` with `<PackageType>Template</PackageType>` (or a `.nuspec`) to actually produce a NuGet package.\n\nThe `groupIdentity` gap is the most impactful — without it, users who install v1 and then update to v2 will end up with both versions listed.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"516d8db2-e787-4cfe-b6de-e7405b7f566e","outputTokens":306,"requestId":"0405:1005AF:ADF287:D82FC4:6A012A84"},"id":"80f90611-bd65-4a0d-a38d-0193548a0ef7","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:02:09.921Z","parentId":"3b503c20-b804-4ea4-bcbe-230948e54375"}
